{
  "metadata": {
    "type": "targeted_grid",
    "name": "targeted_sweep3_econ_friction",
    "description": "Map the effect of economic friction parameters on cascade dynamics.\nTests econ_inertia (switching friction/infrastructure costs) against econ_switching_threshold (minimum price advantage needed to switch).\nThese parameters showed medium correlation in exploratory sweeps:\n  - econ_inertia: -0.324 (higher = slower switching)\n  - econ_switching_threshold: +0.330 (higher = needs bigger gap)\n\nFixed at economic_split=0.65 \u2014 in the zone where cascades are possible but not guaranteed. The question: can high friction block a cascade, or does the economic signal eventually break through regardless?\nKey questions:\n  - At high friction (inertia=0.35, threshold=0.28), is the cascade blocked?\n  - At low friction (inertia=0.05, threshold=0.05), does cascade happen faster?\n  - Is there a threshold combination where outcome changes?\n",
    "spec_file": "specs/targeted_sweep3_econ_friction.yaml",
    "n_samples": 16,
    "n_parameters": 16,
    "grid_axes": {
      "econ_inertia": [
        0.05,
        0.15,
        0.25,
        0.35
      ],
      "econ_switching_threshold": [
        0.05,
        0.12,
        0.2,
        0.28
      ]
    },
    "fixed_parameters": {
      "economic_split": 0.65,
